---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Home" activeSection="home">

  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden" style="background: #0f1419;">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 opacity-[0.03]" style="background-image: radial-gradient(circle at 20% 50%, #c9a84c 1px, transparent 1px), radial-gradient(circle at 80% 30%, #3d8b8b 1px, transparent 1px); background-size: 60px 60px;"></div>

    <div class="relative max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-20 sm:py-28 text-center">
      <p style="font-family: sans-serif; color: #c9a84c; font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.2em; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        Erasmus+ KA171 &middot; Comenius University &amp; VNU Hanoi
      </p>

      <h1 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; color: #faf5ee; font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.2rem); font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.2; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        Science, Creation, Contingency,<br/>
        <span style="color: #c9a84c;">and the Human Person</span>
      </h1>

      <div style="max-width: 36rem; margin: 0 auto; color: rgba(250,245,238,0.8); font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.75;">
        <p>
          An interactive scholarly resource exploring what Christian philosophy of science
          and Buddhist philosophy can learn from each other — and what they reveal together
          about human nature in an age of artificial intelligence.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="margin-top: 2.5rem; display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center; gap: 1rem;">
        <a href={`${base}presentation`}
           style="padding: 0.75rem 1.75rem; background: #c9a84c; color: #0f1419; font-family: sans-serif; font-weight: 600; border-radius: 0.5rem; text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.95rem; transition: background 0.2s;"
           onmouseover="this.style.background='#d4b86a'"
           onmouseout="this.style.background='#c9a84c'">
          Read the Presentation
        </a>
        <a href={`${base}about`}
           style="padding: 0.75rem 1.75rem; border: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.3); color: #d6d3d1; font-family: sans-serif; border-radius: 0.5rem; text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.95rem; transition: background 0.2s;"
           onmouseover="this.style.background='rgba(255,255,255,0.05)'"
           onmouseout="this.style.background='transparent'">
          About the Project
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Three Dialogue Partners -->
  <section style="background: #faf5ee; border-top: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.15); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.15);">
    <div style="max-width: 64rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 4rem 1rem;">
      <div style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917;">Three Voices in Dialogue</h2>
        <p style="color: #78716c; max-width: 36rem; margin: 0.75rem auto 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
          Not a contest of worldviews, but a colligation — bringing together insights
          while letting each voice retain its distinctive identity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem;">
        <!-- Christian Philosophy -->
        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 0.75rem; padding: 1.75rem; border: 1px solid #e7e5e4; border-top: 3px solid #c9a84c;">
          <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">✝</p>
          <h3 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Christian Philosophy</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 0.875rem; color: #57534e; line-height: 1.6;">
            Creation, contingency, the <em>imago Dei</em>, and the apophatic tradition. From Augustine
            through Torrance to McGrath — a theological vision of science as a vocation within a created order.
          </p>
        </div>
        <!-- Buddhist Philosophy -->
        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 0.75rem; padding: 1.75rem; border: 1px solid #e7e5e4; border-top: 3px solid #3d8b8b;">
          <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">☸</p>
          <h3 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Buddhist Philosophy</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 0.875rem; color: #57534e; line-height: 1.6;">
            Dependent origination, emptiness, the middle way, and the dissolution of the fixed self.
            From Nāgārjuna through Trần Nhân Tông to Nguyen Hoang Hai — a philosophical engagement
            with modern science through Buddhist principles.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Natural Science -->
        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 0.75rem; padding: 1.75rem; border: 1px solid #e7e5e4; border-top: 3px solid #a85c32;">
          <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">🔬</p>
          <h3 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Natural Science</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 0.875rem; color: #57534e; line-height: 1.6;">
            Quantum mechanics, cosmological fine-tuning, evolutionary biology, neuroscience, and AI.
            The empirical findings that both traditions must engage — and that raise questions
            science itself cannot answer.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Six Acts Overview -->
  <section style="max-width: 52rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 4rem 1rem;">
    <div style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917;">The Argument in Six Acts</h2>
      <p style="color: #78716c; max-width: 32rem; margin: 0.75rem auto 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        A journey from the foundations of science through the encounter with Buddhist thought
        to the limits of human knowledge — and what lies beyond. Click any act to explore its argument.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.75rem;">

      <!-- Act I -->
      <details class="act-card">
        <summary class="act-card__summary">
          <div class="act-card__header">
            <span class="act-card__num" style="color: #c9a84c;">I</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="act-card__title">Creation, Intelligibility, and Contingency</h3>
              <p class="act-card__desc">Why is the universe intelligible? The doctrine of creation as the foundation of scientific inquiry.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="act-card__chevron">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="act-card__content">
          <p class="act-card__thesis" style="border-left-color: #c9a84c;">
            Science became possible when nature was understood not as divine but as <em>created</em> — magnificent, yet not to be worshipped. This freed inquiry: if the Nile is a god, you pray to it; if it is a creature, you can study it.
          </p>
          <ul class="act-card__points">
            <li><strong>Logos and the grammar of being:</strong> The rational structure of the world reflects divine wisdom. The universe has a "grammar" grounded in divine reason, not accident (John 1:1).</li>
            <li><strong>Inner logic doctrine:</strong> Each domain of reality must be engaged <em>according to its own nature</em> — the object determines the method, not vice versa (T. F. Torrance).</li>
            <li><strong>Contingency demands observation:</strong> Because the world is created freely, it <em>could have been otherwise</em>. We must look and observe rather than deduce from pure reason alone.</li>
            <li><strong>Order + Contingency = Science:</strong> Order makes science rational; contingency makes it empirical. Together they give us the intellectual conditions for modern natural science.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="act-card__thinkers"><strong>Key voices:</strong> Thomas F. Torrance, Stanley Jaki, Peter Harrison, Steven Rose</p>
          <a href={`${base}presentation#act-creation`} class="act-card__link">Read Act I in full &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Act II -->
      <details class="act-card">
        <summary class="act-card__summary">
          <div class="act-card__header">
            <span class="act-card__num" style="color: #3d8b8b;">II</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="act-card__title">A Genuine Conversation with Dependent Origination</h3>
              <p class="act-card__desc">Dependent origination as an alternative account of why things exist. Convergences and the fork in the road.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="act-card__chevron">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="act-card__content">
          <p class="act-card__thesis" style="border-left-color: #3d8b8b;">
            All phenomena arise through mutual conditioning; nothing stands alone. Compositionality + impermanence = emptiness (<em>śūnyatā</em>) — the absence of fixed, independent essence. But does the web of dependent origination explain <em>why there is a web at all</em>?
          </p>
          <ul class="act-card__points">
            <li><strong>Rejecting the "Buddhism Problem":</strong> Western scholarship wrongly forces Buddhism into theistic categories. "Religion" is a Western construct, not a natural kind.</li>
            <li><strong>Dependent origination as relational ontology:</strong> Nguyen Hoang Hai demonstrates compositionality and impermanence from subatomic particles to consciousness, proving emptiness at every level.</li>
            <li><strong>Convergence — both reject the autonomous self:</strong> Christianity insists persons are relational by nature (Trinitarian being); Buddhism insists on radical interdependence.</li>
            <li><strong>The fork in the road:</strong> Buddhism: the web <em>is</em> fundamental reality, no transcendent ground needed. Christianity: the web itself is grounded in a transcendent Source. The web does not explain why there is a web.</li>
            <li><strong>Colligation, not syncretism:</strong> The traditions are brought together to see a larger pattern, not merged. Each retains its distinctive voice.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="act-card__thinkers"><strong>Key voices:</strong> Nāgārjuna, Nguyen Hoang Hai, Alasdair MacIntyre, Alister McGrath</p>
          <a href={`${base}presentation#act-buddhism`} class="act-card__link">Read Act II in full &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Act III -->
      <details class="act-card">
        <summary class="act-card__summary">
          <div class="act-card__header">
            <span class="act-card__num" style="color: #c9a84c;">III</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="act-card__title">The Person Who Knows</h3>
              <p class="act-card__desc">What is the human person? Four understandings of the <em>imago Dei</em> meet the Buddhist no-self.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="act-card__chevron">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="act-card__content">
          <p class="act-card__thesis" style="border-left-color: #c9a84c;">
            Science is not a neutral method but a practice of <em>persons</em>. If the knower is merely an adaptive algorithm optimized for survival, then what grounds scientific <em>truthfulness</em>? The capacity for rational inquiry, self-transcendence, and moral responsibility are constitutive of personhood.
          </p>
          <ul class="act-card__points">
            <li><strong>Imago Dei — four understandings:</strong> Sovereignty (the king's representative), correspondence (rational soul reflecting the Creator), relationality (created for communion), and story-telling (co-creators with God).</li>
            <li><strong>Relational but irreducible:</strong> If the self has no enduring center, who is the moral agent? Who repents? Who is responsible? The person is relational but retains an irreducible <em>ipseity</em> — a gift of being called into existence.</li>
            <li><strong>The AI test:</strong> If science is only pattern-matching, AI can replace humans. But if science requires <em>understanding</em> — a person capable of truth, self-correction, asking "why?" — then the knower is irreducible.</li>
            <li><strong>Knowledge as ethical vocation:</strong> Inquiry is a moral calling ordered toward the good, not merely a technique for power (Luther's <em>coram Deo</em>).</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="act-card__thinkers"><strong>Key voices:</strong> Blaise Pascal, Martin Luther, Nguyen Hoang Hai, Richard Dawkins, Alister McGrath</p>
          <a href={`${base}presentation#act-person`} class="act-card__link">Read Act III in full &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Act IV -->
      <details class="act-card">
        <summary class="act-card__summary">
          <div class="act-card__header">
            <span class="act-card__num" style="color: #a85c32;">IV</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="act-card__title">The Limits of Science</h3>
              <p class="act-card__desc">Can science establish values? The three impulses of scientism and the metaquestions science cannot answer.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="act-card__chevron">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="act-card__content">
          <p class="act-card__thesis" style="border-left-color: #a85c32;">
            Science excels at measurable patterns, causal regularities, repeatable phenomena. But it cannot answer why something rather than nothing exists, whether humans have intrinsic dignity, what knowledge is <em>for</em>, or what we ought to do. These are not irrational questions — they are trans-scientific.
          </p>
          <ul class="act-card__points">
            <li><strong>The three impulses of scientism (Ian Kidd):</strong> The imperialist urge (extending science into ethics and metaphysics), the salvific urge (expecting science to satisfy existential needs), and the absolutist urge (claiming totalizing completeness).</li>
            <li><strong>The vicious circle:</strong> Scientism makes philosophical claims <em>about</em> science that cannot be verified <em>by</em> science. It must assume its own authority to confirm itself (Feser).</li>
            <li><strong>A tension in Nguyen's work:</strong> If consciousness evolved for "appropriateness, not truthfulness," what distinguishes genuine wisdom from a convincing illusion? Is the book itself an "appropriate" model — or actually <em>true</em>?</li>
            <li><strong>The "bizarrely restrictive view":</strong> A single perspective allowed to become normative produces a restrictive view of meaning (Mary Midgley). Both traditions resist this narrowing.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="act-card__thinkers"><strong>Key voices:</strong> Ian James Kidd, Edward Feser, Mary Midgley, T. F. Torrance, Kurt Gödel</p>
          <a href={`${base}presentation#act-limits`} class="act-card__link">Read Act IV in full &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Act V -->
      <details class="act-card">
        <summary class="act-card__summary">
          <div class="act-card__header">
            <span class="act-card__num" style="color: #c9a84c;">V</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="act-card__title">Mystery: The Trans-Rational</h3>
              <p class="act-card__desc">When models fail. The apophatic tradition, the numinous, and the emptiness of emptiness.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="act-card__chevron">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="act-card__content">
          <p class="act-card__thesis" style="border-left-color: #c9a84c;">
            Mystery is not irrationality but the <em>trans-rational</em> — what overwhelms and saturates rational capacity precisely because it is <em>more</em> than we can think. Both the Christian apophatic tradition and Buddhist śūnyatā cultivate resistance to reducing reality to our current concepts.
          </p>
          <ul class="act-card__points">
            <li><strong>The numinous (Rudolf Otto):</strong> The <em>mysterium tremendum et fascinans</em> — awe, terror, and fascination before the "wholly other." Trans-rational, not irrational.</li>
            <li><strong>The iron cage (Max Weber):</strong> Rationalism's <em>stahlhartes Gehäuse</em> confines existence to efficiency and control. Mystery cracks that shell open.</li>
            <li><strong>Apophatic and śūnyatā as convergent:</strong> The Christian <em>via negativa</em> (Gregory of Nyssa, Meister Eckhart) and Buddhist prajñāpāramitā share epistemic humility. Both resist idolizing concepts. But the apophatic says God <em>exceeds</em> categories (superabundant being); Buddhism says phenomena <em>lack</em> inherent nature.</li>
            <li><strong>The verum-factum principle (Vico):</strong> We fully grasp only what we construct. Nature and God are realities we did not make and cannot fully master.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="act-card__thinkers"><strong>Key voices:</strong> Rudolf Otto, Max Weber, Gregory of Nyssa, Nāgārjuna, Giambattista Vico, Richard Feynman</p>
          <a href={`${base}presentation#act-mystery`} class="act-card__link">Read Act V in full &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Closing -->
      <details class="act-card act-card--closing">
        <summary class="act-card__summary">
          <div class="act-card__header">
            <span class="act-card__num" style="color: #a85c32;">&hearts;</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="act-card__title">What Happens to Love?</h3>
              <p class="act-card__desc">If the self is relational, what grounds the reality of love? The deepest question between our two traditions.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="act-card__chevron">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="act-card__content">
          <p class="act-card__thesis" style="border-left-color: #a85c32;">
            If the self is an illusion crafted by DNA, then love is too — just another adaptive strategy. But if love is <em>real</em>, if a mother's love is not merely a dopamine-mediated survival mechanism but a genuine participation in something transcendent, then reality cannot be exhausted by compositionality and impermanence.
          </p>
          <ul class="act-card__points">
            <li><strong>Four pillars of the argument:</strong> The world is <em>created</em> (real, intelligible), <em>contingent</em> (requiring observation and humility), <em>personal</em> (the knower is a moral agent), and <em>limited yet open</em> (science must converse with philosophy and theology).</li>
            <li><strong>From information to wisdom:</strong> We drown in information while starving for wisdom (E. O. Wilson). Wisdom is colligation — deeper rationality, integration of insights and their application to life.</li>
            <li><strong>The pressing question:</strong> If consciousness models reality for <em>adaptive survival</em> rather than <em>truth</em>, what grounds scientific responsibility for truthfulness? What sustains the moral continuity of inquiry?</li>
            <li><strong>Love as irreducible:</strong> Love points to a dimension that is relational <em>and</em> personal, temporal <em>and</em> eternal, vulnerable <em>and</em> unconditional. The Christian claim grounds this in the triune God as eternal communion of persons.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="act-card__thinkers"><strong>Key voices:</strong> E. O. Wilson, Aristotle (<em>phronesis</em>), Nguyen Hoang Hai, Alister McGrath</p>
          <a href={`${base}presentation#closing`} class="act-card__link">Read the Closing in full &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </details>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Author & Context -->
  <section style="background: #0f1419; border-top: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.15); padding: 4rem 1rem; text-align: center;">
    <p style="font-family: sans-serif; color: #78716c; font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.15em; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Presented by</p>
    <p style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; color: #faf5ee; font-size: 1.5rem;">prof. PhDr. Michal Valčo, PhD.</p>
    <p style="color: #a8a29e; font-size: 0.875rem; margin-top: 0.25rem;">Evangelical Lutheran Theological Faculty, Comenius University in Bratislava</p>
    <p style="color: #78716c; font-size: 0.8rem; margin-top: 1rem; max-width: 32rem; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
      Guest lecture delivered at the Tran Nhan Tong Institute, Vietnam National University, Hanoi &middot; March 12, 2026
    </p>
    <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      <a href={`${base}presentation`}
         style="display: inline-block; padding: 0.6rem 1.5rem; background: #c9a84c; color: #0f1419; font-family: sans-serif; font-weight: 600; border-radius: 0.5rem; text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.9rem;">
        Begin Reading →
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
